# Fleet Project Standard

> The standardized approach for managing long-term projects across this fleet.
> Every managed project follows this standard; `/project-init` creates projects that
> conform to it, and `/project-steward` (autonomous, scheduled) manages them against it.
> **{{AGENT_NAME}}** is the managing agent; fleet agents execute dispatched work;
> **{{OPERATOR}}** is the operator (the human this standard escalates to).
>
> Version: 1.0 ({{DATE}})

## 1. Where projects live

| Thing | Location | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Registry (source of truth for status) | GitHub issues in `{{REGISTRY_REPO}}` | One **epic issue** per project, label `project`. Query: `gh issue list --label project --state open` |
| Workspace (files, drafts, outputs) | `project_files/<slug>/` in the managing agent's repo | Free-form except `project.md` (charter). Path is recorded in the epic body — never derived from the slug. **May be local-only**: if `project_files/` is gitignored, agents running on Trinity never see workspaces — the epic body is the authoritative context there. |
| Steward state, digests, run log, Trinity-run outputs | `fleet/project-steward/` | Written only by `/project-steward`; tracked in git and pushed after each run (GitHub carries steward state between local and Trinity runs) |

There is **no separate project index file**. GitHub is the registry; folders are workspaces.
Duplicate state is a bug.

## 2. Roles

- **{{AGENT_NAME}}** — the manager and the **sole writer of GitHub issues**. All labels,
  comments, and status changes go through the managing agent. Fleet agents do not write
  issues directly (most have no access to the registry repo); they report results in chat
  and the manager relays them to the issue log. This keeps the record standardized and
  enforceable in one place.
- **{{OPERATOR}}** — decides anything labeled `status:needs-operator`, sets priorities,
  approves project creation/closure when it has external consequences.
- **Fleet agents** — execute dispatched tasks and reply in the same Trinity chat with a
  result summary. They never manage the project record.

## 3. Label taxonomy

| Label | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `project` | Marks a project **epic** issue (exactly one per project) |
| `task` | Marks a task issue belonging to some project |
| `project:<slug>` | Membership — ties task issues to their project epic |
| `status:active` | Being worked; steward manages it normally |
| `status:blocked` | Progress stopped by an external dependency (state the blocker in a comment) |
| `status:needs-operator` | A decision or action only the operator can take; steward will not act, only escalate |
| `status:paused` | Deliberately on hold; steward skips it (no staleness escalation) |
| `priority:p1` / `priority:p2` / `priority:p3` | p1 = steward reviews first and escalates fastest |
| `agent:<name>` | Owner agent for dispatchable work (`agent:{{AGENT_NAME}}` when the managing agent does the work itself). Names must match `fleet/system-map.yaml` |

Rules: every epic carries `project`, exactly one `status:*`, one `priority:*`, and at least
one `agent:*`. Slugs are kebab-case. Labels are created idempotently by `/project-init`.

## 4. Epic issue anatomy

Title: `[Project] <Name>`

Body sections (all required; keep them current):

```markdown
## Goal
One paragraph: what done looks like and why it matters.

## Success criteria
- [ ] Measurable outcome 1
- [ ] Measurable outcome 2

## Workspace
`project_files/<slug>/`

## Owner agents
- <agent-name> — <what they own>

## Cadence notes
Anything timing-related: deadlines, external events, review rhythm.

## Current status
(maintained by /project-steward — do not hand-edit; latest steward update wins)

## Tasks
- [ ] #NN Task title (checked when the task issue closes)
```

## 5. Task issue anatomy

Title: plain imperative (`Draft the trademark response letter`), no prefix.
Labels: `task` + `project:<slug>` + `agent:<name>` if dispatchable.

Body:

```markdown
## Objective
What this task accomplishes.

## Definition of done
Concrete, checkable finish line.

## Context
Links: epic #NN, relevant files in the workspace, prior work.
```

Tasks are listed as a checklist in the epic. One task issue = one dispatchable unit of
work sized for a single agent session (under ~45 minutes of agent work). Bigger work gets
split before dispatch.

## 6. Comment conventions (written only by the managing agent)

**Steward update** — posted by `/project-steward` only when something changed since the
last update (no heartbeat spam):

```markdown
### Steward update YYYY-MM-DD
- Status: active | blocked | needs-operator | paused
- Since last: <what happened, or "no activity">
- Dispatched: <agent> — <task #NN> | none
- Blockers: <blocker> | none
- Next: <planned next action>
```

**Dispatch receipt** — posted at dispatch time on the task issue:

```markdown
### Dispatched YYYY-MM-DD
Sent to `<agent>` via Trinity chat. Expected deliverable: <summary>.
```

**Agent report relay** — posted when the agent's chat reply is reconciled:

```markdown
### Agent report YYYY-MM-DD (<agent>)
<verbatim or tightly summarized result, with links/paths>
```

## 7. Lifecycle

```
proposed -> active -> (blocked | needs-operator | paused)* -> done
```

- **Create** via `/project-init` (new or adopt-mode for an existing folder). New epics
  start `status:active` unless stated otherwise.
- **Blocked / needs-operator / paused** are set by the steward or by the operator; they
  are states of the epic, not the end of it.
- **Done**: all success criteria checked → steward proposes closure in the digest; the
  operator (or the managing agent on explicit instruction) closes the epic. Closing the
  epic archives the project; the workspace folder stays (add a final note in `project.md`).

## 8. Staleness policy

Measured from the last activity on the epic or its open tasks (comments, label changes,
commits referencing the issue):

- **7 days** with no activity on an `active` project → steward investigates: reads the
  workspace and open tasks, and either dispatches the next task or explains the stall in a
  steward update.
- **14 days** → steward sets `status:needs-operator` and puts it at the top of the digest.
- `status:paused` projects are exempt.

## 9. Dispatch protocol

The steward dispatches work to fleet agents via Trinity `chat_with_agent`. Rules:

1. **Explicit ownership only.** Dispatch only to the agent named by the task's (or epic's)
   `agent:*` label. Never fuzzy-match an owner at runtime; ambiguity → `status:needs-operator`.
   (This is why the steward never needs `/orchestrate`'s routing judgment — see §11.)
2. **Resolve through the map, respect the boundaries.** The `agent:*` label is the *logical*
   name — resolve it to the live callable name via `fleet/system-map.yaml` (`deployed_name`,
   falling back to the last segment of `ref:`). If `fleet/orchestration.md` §5 does not
   sanction a manager→owner edge, do **not** dispatch — set `status:needs-operator` and say
   which edge is missing (an autonomous run must never silently violate the permission intent).
3. **Health check first.** `get_agent_health` before dispatch; unhealthy or stopped agent →
   note it, set `status:blocked`, escalate in digest.
4. **One open dispatch per project** at a time; **max 3 dispatches per steward run** fleet-wide.
5. **Standard brief** (the chat message):

```
[PROJECT DISPATCH] <project name> — <task title>
Issue: <task issue URL>
Objective: <from the task body>
Definition of done: <from the task body>
Context: <key links/paths the agent needs>
Deliverable: reply in this chat with a result summary and links/paths.
<managing agent> relays your reply to the issue log — do not attempt to write GitHub issues.
```

6. **`agent:{{AGENT_NAME}}` tasks are never dispatched via Trinity** (the steward *is* the
   managing agent — a chat dispatch would loop). The steward executes them inline if they
   fit the run budget, otherwise lists them in the digest as manager to-dos for the next
   interactive session.
7. **Reconciliation.** Open dispatches are tracked in the steward's state file. On each run
   the steward reads the agent's chat reply, posts an agent-report relay comment, checks the
   task off (or reopens with findings), and clears the tracker entry. No reply after 6 hours →
   re-ping once; nothing after 24 hours → `status:blocked` + digest escalation.
8. **External effects stay gated downstream.** Dispatched agents keep their own human gates
   (draft-only email, operator queue, etc.). The steward never asks an agent to bypass one.

## 10. Workspace folder standard

```
project_files/<slug>/
  project.md        <- charter: mirrors the epic (goal, criteria, links), plus local notes
  ...               <- everything else free-form (drafts, data, outputs)
```

`project.md` must link to the epic issue URL. The epic body must record the workspace path.

## 11. Skills that operate this standard

| Skill | Automation | Role |
|---|---|---|
| `/project-init` | manual | Create or adopt a project conforming to this standard |
| `/project-steward` | autonomous (every 2h during working hours, weekdays — installer-configured) | Sweep, reconcile dispatches, dispatch/execute next work, escalate, digest; no-op runs leave no trace |

`/orchestrate` is deliberately **not** in this table: the steward dispatches only to
explicitly-labeled owners (no routing judgment), because `/orchestrate`'s interactive
disambiguation would hang an autonomous run. Ad-hoc cross-agent work still goes through
`/orchestrate`; *managed project* work goes through this standard.

Change this standard deliberately: it is read by both skills at runtime, so edits here
change fleet behavior without touching the skills.
